reasonable conclusion to be drawn on the figures provided</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, nor by their own understanding, legitimate comparison between forces.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The advent of the PCCs has also had a positive impact in this area.  A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s they are electable positions and therefore accountable for the pledges they have made there is a keener sense that the crime data should be more ethical and correct.  It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">more significant when a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> force shows a reduction in crime, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> they are audited by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> an external agency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Has enough been done to ensure the integrity of crime data? What more should be done?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The victim based approach means evaluation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">whether to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> record as a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> crime or not should be based on the initial information provided</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are oft</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">en being reminded that HOCR and NCRS is fit for purpose but there are always numerous 'slight' changes being made and various offences being moved between sections.  This will make any future comparisons difficult if not impossible.  Next year will see a h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">uge change in the way that forces record outcomes which may well add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> inadvertently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> another performance indicator between forces.  To ensure that crime data will be appropriately comparable over the foreseeable future and allow forces to go forward in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> knowledge that the playing field will not be changed there should (in my view) be no further large scale changes to HOCR.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Sussex Police has moved a long way from red/green targets to developing performance products that really help to understand the busi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ness.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">This contributes to achieving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ethical recording.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent can policy-makers have confidence in the statistics which result from the recording of crime by police forces?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Whilst it is clear that all forces have issues around the same sort of i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ncident</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (ABH v Common Assault, Criminal Damage v Burglary and mobile phone theft) I still feel that a reasonable amount of confidence can remain in the crime statistics.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Should recorded crime statistics be classified as National Statistics?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0p